\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 1.                  Paliurus}                   Miller
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc By †T.G. Tutin.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Stipules spinescent. Flowers 5-merous, hermaphrodite. Styles 2-3. Fruit dry, hemispherical, with a wide membranous wing round the top.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. P. spina-christi} Miller, {\i Gard. Dict.} ed. 8 (1768) ({\i P. australis} Gaertner). Nearly glabrous, much-branched shrub up to c. 3 m. Twigs flexuous, puberulent when young. Leaves 2-4 cm, alternate and distichous, ovate, crenate-serrate, shortly petiolate. Flowers in small, axillary, shortly pedunculate cymes. Fruit 18-30 mm in diameter; wing undulate.{\i  Dry slopes; also often used for hedges. Mediterranean region} ({\i except the islands}),{\i  Balkan peninsula and Black Sea coast.} Al Bu Ga Gr Hs It Ju Rm Rs (K) Tu [Co Hu].
\par

\par

