\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. Z. jujuba} Miller, {\i Gard. Dict.} ed. 8, no. 1 (1768). Shrub or small tree up to 8 m. Twigs flexuous, glabrous when young, green. Leaves 2-5·5 cm, alternate, oblong, obtuse, glandular-denticulate, shortly petiolate. Flowers few, in a small, axillary cyme which is longer than its peduncle. Drupe 1·5-3 cm, ovoid-oblong, dark reddish or almost black, edible. {\i Cultivated in S. Europe for its edible fruits and frequently naturalized in the Mediterranean region and on the Black Sea coast. }[Al Bu Cr Ga Gr Hs It Ju Rm Si Tu.] ({\i Temperate Asia}.)
\par

\par

